<paragraph id="8B9C36C3FFAEFFB680B6F9EEFB63F96A" blockId="6.[151,1437,1182,2038]" pageId="6" pageNumber="377">
<emphasis id="B957EAD1FFAEFFB680B6F9EEFEBAF9C5" bold="true" box="[199,322,1542,1569]" pageId="6" pageNumber="377">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C234D40FFAEFFB68139F9E0FDCEF9C5" box="[328,566,1543,1569]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Peripus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="madrededios">
<emphasis id="B957EAD1FFAEFFB68139F9E0FDCEF9C5" box="[328,566,1543,1569]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="377">Peripus madrededios</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is one of the two species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C234D40FFAEFFB68300F9E0FC30F9C5" authority="Chatzimanolis, 2019" authorityName="Chatzimanolis" authorityYear="2019" box="[881,968,1544,1569]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Peripus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="371" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis id="B957EAD1FFAEFFB68300F9E0FC30F9C5" box="[881,968,1544,1569]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="377">Peripus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(along with 
<taxonomicName id="4C234D40FFAEFFB68424F9E0FB28F9C5" box="[1109,1232,1543,1569]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Peripus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="didontus">
<emphasis id="B957EAD1FFAEFFB68424F9E0FB28F9C5" box="[1109,1232,1543,1569]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="377">P. didontus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) with two subapical teeth on the median lobe. Unlike 
<taxonomicName id="4C234D40FFAEFFB68245F9C4FD57F9A1" box="[564,687,1579,1605]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Peripus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="didontus">
<emphasis id="B957EAD1FFAEFFB68245F9C4FD57F9A1" box="[564,687,1579,1605]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="377">P. didontus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the punctation of the pronotum is not contiguous and there are (at least) three rows of punctures in addition to the punctures along the midline. Additionally, antennomeres 8–10 are subquadrate to slightly elongate in 
<taxonomicName id="4C234D40FFAEFFB68251F99CFD33F969" box="[544,715,1651,1677]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Peripus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="madrededios">
<emphasis id="B957EAD1FFAEFFB68251F99CFD33F969" box="[544,715,1651,1677]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="377">P. madrededios</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(clearly longer than wide in 
<taxonomicName id="4C234D40FFAEFFB6847FF99CFB72F969" box="[1038,1162,1651,1677]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Peripus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="didontus">
<emphasis id="B957EAD1FFAEFFB6847FF99CFB72F969" box="[1038,1162,1651,1677]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="377">P. didontus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9C36C3FFAEFFB680B6F97EFE48F8FA" blockId="6.[151,1437,1182,2038]" pageId="6" pageNumber="377">
<emphasis id="B957EAD1FFAEFFB680B6F97EFEA1F955" bold="true" box="[199,345,1686,1713]" pageId="6" pageNumber="377">Description.</emphasis>
Forebody length 
<quantity id="4CDB9B26FFAEFFB68251F97EFD52F956" box="[544,682,1686,1714]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.35" metricValueMax="5.5" metricValueMin="5.2" pageId="6" pageNumber="377" unit="mm" value="5.35" valueMax="5.5" valueMin="5.2">5.2–5.5 mm</quantity>
. Coloration of head and pronotum dark metallic blue purple; elytra brighter, metallic blue-green; mesoscutellum and ventral forebody shiny brown; mouthparts and antennae light brown to brown; legs brown except joints and tarsi yellowish brown; abdomen brown except posterior ½ to 2/5 of segment 7, and 8 orange.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9C36C3FFAEFFB680B6F8CFFE4DF811" blockId="6.[151,1437,1182,2038]" pageId="6" pageNumber="377">Head with 2–3 rows of punctures on each side of central impunctate area; with dense micropunctures and microsculpture. Head width/length ratio = 1.28; antennomere 8 longer than wide; antennomeres 9–10 subquadrate to slightly elongate. Pronotum subquadrate, width/length ratio = 0.97; with 3–5 rows of scattered punctures in addition to rows of punctures flanking impunctate center; punctures not contiguous; impunctate area in middle as wide as 3–4 punctures, but impunctate area wider posteriorly; with dense micropunctures and microsculpture. Pronotum/ elytra length ratio = 0.99.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9C36C3FFAFFFB780B6FF71FEABFEFB" blockId="7.[151,1436,153,431]" pageId="7" pageNumber="378">
Aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation id="13182A46FFAFFFB78104FF71FE03FF57" box="[373,507,153,179]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–29" captionStartId="10.[151,264,936,961]" captionTargetBox="[151,1425,181,905]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,181,916]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 27–29. Aedeagus of P. madrededios Chatzimanolis &amp; Hightower. 27. Dorsal view. 28. Lateral view. 29. Detail of paramere, ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3354792/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="378">Figs. 27–29</figureCitation>
; in dorsal view paramere converging to pointed apex; paramere longer but narrower than median lobe; in lateral view paramere concave; paramere with peg setae as in 
<figureCitation id="13182A46FFAFFFB78434FF55FB61FF33" box="[1093,1177,189,215]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–29" captionStartId="10.[151,264,936,961]" captionTargetBox="[151,1425,181,905]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,181,916]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 27–29. Aedeagus of P. madrededios Chatzimanolis &amp; Hightower. 27. Dorsal view. 28. Lateral view. 29. Detail of paramere, ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3354792/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="378">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
. Median lobe in dorsal view converging to rounded apex; median lobe with two subapical teeth; in lateral view median lobe becoming narrower near apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9C36C3FFAFFFB780B6FEC1FE06FE83" blockId="7.[151,1436,153,431]" pageId="7" pageNumber="378">
<emphasis id="B957EAD1FFAFFFB780B6FEC1FEB6FEA7" bold="true" box="[199,334,297,323]" pageId="7" pageNumber="378">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is derived from the name of the department of 
<collectingCountry id="F3347653FFAFFFB78426FEC1FB72FEA7" box="[1111,1162,297,323]" name="Peru" pageId="7" pageNumber="378">Peru</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="49E7F821FFAFFFB784EBFEC1FABFFEA0" box="[1178,1351,297,324]" country="Peru" name="Madre de Dios" pageId="7" pageNumber="378">Madre de Dios</collectingRegion>
) where these specimens were collected.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9C36C3FFAFFFB780B6FE98FC28FE6F" blockId="7.[151,1436,153,431]" box="[199,976,368,395]" pageId="7" pageNumber="378">
<emphasis id="B957EAD1FFAFFFB780B6FE98FE99FE6F" bold="true" box="[199,353,368,395]" pageId="7" pageNumber="378">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known from the department of 
<collectingRegion id="49E7F821FFAFFFB782BAFE99FC89FE6F" box="[715,881,369,395]" country="Peru" name="Madre de Dios" pageId="7" pageNumber="378">Madre de Dios</collectingRegion>
in 
<collectingCountry id="F3347653FFAFFFB783E4FE99FC34FE6F" box="[917,972,369,395]" name="Peru" pageId="7" pageNumber="378">Peru</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9C36C3FFAFFFB780B6FE7CFAC2FE4B" blockId="7.[151,1436,153,431]" box="[199,1338,404,431]" pageId="7" pageNumber="378">
<emphasis id="B957EAD1FFAFFFB780B6FE7CFED2FE4B" bold="true" box="[199,298,404,431]" pageId="7" pageNumber="378">Habitat.</emphasis>
Collected in lowland tropical rainforests (elevations 
<quantity id="4CDB9B26FFAFFFB7830CFE7DFC05FE4B" box="[893,1021,405,431]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.55" metricValueMax="4.2" metricValueMin="2.9" pageId="7" pageNumber="378" unit="m" value="355.0" valueMax="420.0" valueMin="290.0">290–420 m</quantity>
) using flight intercept traps.
</paragraph>
